**New Dinner Options**

Good move thinking about dinner systemically — this is where the component approach really earns its keep, because dinners are where you can do most of the heavy lifting on the ratio. Breakfast and lunch are often constrained (portable, quick, cold-friendly), but dinner is where you can deliberately combine an omega-3 protein source, an omega-3-friendly fat, and lower-omega-6 carbs in one sitting.

Before laying it out, two things worth flagging upfront so the framework lands on the right foundations:

- Jane being pescatarian (rather than strictly vegetarian) genuinely changes the dinner picture. Oily fish — mackerel, sardines, salmon, anchovies, herring, trout — are the single most effective omega-3 lever you have, and getting them in 2–3 dinners a week would do more for your ratio than almost anything else combined.

- Topping choices and the cooking fat are where omega-6 sneaks back in. Pastry, store-bought breadcrumbs, anything fried in sunflower oil, and crumbles using cheap "vegetable oil" all undo the work the filling is doing. So toppings need the same scrutiny as fillings.

Here's how I'd structure the component framework:

**1. The Base (the saucy/protein-bearing layer)**

This is the workhorse — usually batch-cookable, often improves on day two, carries most of the protein.

**Vegetarian bases** (Jane-friendly, low omega-6 if cooked in olive/rapeseed oil):

- Lentil & white bean ragù (Mediterranean, herb-led)

- North African spiced lentil & chickpea (your shepherd's pie filling sits here)

- Mushroom & puy lentil "bolognese"

- Ratatouille with cannellini beans

- Black bean & sweet potato chilli

- Saag-style spinach & chickpea

- Dal — tarka, makhani-style (with coconut not cream), or red lentil & tomato

**Pescatarian bases** (omega-3 powerhouses):

- Salmon & leek (poached salmon flaked through a leek and white bean base)

- Smoked mackerel & tomato (mackerel flaked into a tomato/caper base)

- Sardine puttanesca-style

- White fish & butter bean stew (cod, hake, pollock with tomato and chorizo-paprika notes — chorizo optional)

- Tuna & cannellini (proper tinned-in-olive-oil tuna, not sunflower oil)

- Anchovy & lentil (anchovies melted into a base — they disappear, leaving umami)

- Fish pie filling (revisited — dairy-free béchamel made with oat milk and a little miso)

**2. The Topping (or Carb Carrier if no topping)**

This is where your shepherd's pie example really opens up. Toppings can sit *on* a base (pie-style) or *under/alongside* it (bowl-style).

**Mash family:**

- Classic potato mash (with olive oil and a splash of oat milk rather than butter/cream)

- Sweet potato mash (sweeter, pairs well with North African and chilli bases)

- Celeriac & potato mash (lower-carb, better for fish pies)

- Mixed root mash — parsnip, carrot, potato (good with shepherd's pie style)

- Cauliflower mash (works under fish bases)

- Butter bean & potato mash (sneaks more pulses in)

**Sliced potato family:**

- Boulangère (sliced potato baked over filling with stock — naturally dairy-free)

- Hasselback-style sliced potato lid

- Thinly sliced sweet potato lid

**Grain ****&**** seed toppings:**

- Oat & seed crumble (oats, flaxseed, walnut, herbs, olive oil — rare topping that *adds* omega-3)

- Polenta crust (creamy or set then sliced and grilled)

- Bulgur or freekeh "pilaf lid"

**Pastry — handle with care:**

- Homemade rough puff with rapeseed oil-based pastry is fine occasionally; shop-bought puff and filo are almost universally sunflower oil

**Carb-alongside (not on top):**

- Brown rice, basmati, freekeh, pearl barley, farro

- Sourdough or seeded bread

- Homemade flatbread (rapeseed oil)

**3. The Vegetable Layer**

Either built into the base or served alongside. Worth treating as a deliberate component because it's an easy place to stack omega-3 ALA via leafy greens (kale, spring greens, chard, watercress).

- Steamed/braised greens with lemon and olive oil

- Roasted Mediterranean veg (peppers, courgette, aubergine)

- Slow-roasted tomatoes

- Charred broccoli or tenderstem

- Slaw with rapeseed-oil dressing

- Air-fryer roast roots (your Ninja gets a workout here)

**4. The Finisher (sauces, fats, garnishes)**

Often overlooked but this is your most precise omega 3:6 control point. Most ratio damage in "healthy" cooking happens at this stage via shop-bought sauces and dressings.

- Salsa verde (parsley, capers, anchovy, olive oil)

- Tahini-yogurt sauce (using oat or soy yogurt)

- Chermoula (coriander, cumin, lemon, olive oil)

- Walnut & herb pesto with rapeseed oil

- Lemon-tahini drizzle

- Pickled red onion / quick pickles

- Toasted flaxseed/walnut/hemp seed sprinkle

- A swirl of good extra virgin olive oil or cold-pressed rapeseed

The combinatorial effect is what makes this powerful: 6 vegetarian bases × 5 mash variations × 5 finishers = 150 distinct dinners before you even bring fish into it.

A few worked examples to show how it plays out:

- **North African lentil base** + sweet potato mash + chermoula drizzle + steamed greens

- **Smoked mackerel ****&**** tomato base** + sliced potato lid + lemon-caper dressing + watercress

- **Mushroom ****&**** puy lentil ragù** + polenta lid + walnut-parsley pesto + roast tenderstem

- **Salmon ****&**** leek base** + celeriac-potato mash + salsa verde + buttered (oat-buttered) peas